{"cursor":"12499","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"In the mathematical field of graph theory, an 'automorphism' of a graph is a\nform of symmetry in which the graph is mapped onto itself while preserving the\nedgeâvertex connectivity.\n\nFormally, an automorphism of a graph G = (V,E) is a permutation Ï of\nthe vertex set V, such that the pair of vertices (u,v) form an edge if and only\nif the pair (Ï(u),Ï(v)) also form an edge. That is, it is a graph isomorphism\nfrom G to itself. Automorphisms may be defined in this way both for directed\ngraphs and for undirected graphs. The composition of two automorphisms is\nanother automorphism, and the set of automorphisms of a given graph, under the\ncomposition operation, forms a group, the automorphism group of the graph. In\nthe opposite direction, by Frucht's theorem, all groups can be represented as\nthe automorphism group of a connected graph â indeed, of a cubic\ngraph. . | year=1949 | journal=Canadian Journal of Mathematics |\nissn=0008-414X | volume=1 | pages=365â378 | doi=10.4153/CJM-1949-033-6 |\nissue=4}}.\n","linknr":267,"url":"Graph_automorphism_problem","recorded":1362674115,"links":47,"instances":["mathematics","mathematics"],"pdf":["http://theorie.informatik.uni-ulm.de/Personen/toran/papers/hard.pdf","http://cs.anu.edu.au/people/bdm/nauty/pgi.pdf","http://cs.anu.edu.au/people/bdm/nauty/pgi.pdf","http://www.siam.org/proceedings/alenex/2007/alx07_013junttilat.pdf","http://www.siam.org/proceedings/alenex/2007/alx07_013junttilat.pdf","http://vlsicad.eecs.umich.edu/BK/SAUCY/saucy-dac08.pdf","http://vlsicad.eecs.umich.edu/BK/SAUCY/saucy-dac08.pdf","http://www.eecs.umich.edu/~imarkov/pubs/conf/sat10-sym.pdf","http://www.eecs.umich.edu/~imarkov/pubs/conf/sat10-sym.pdf"],"categories":["Algebraic graph theory"],"headings":["Computational complexity","Algorithms, software and applications","Symmetry display","Graph families defined by their automorphisms","See also","References"],"image":["//